\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {12}{\ignorespaces Cross-UID hijack outcomes by attack sub-case (\texttt  {blind}, \texttt  {guessed}, \texttt  {leaked}) and binary state, $n = 500$ per panel. Panel (a) is the stock module: only the \texttt  {leaked} sub-case (where UID $B$ has obtained UID $A$'s 64-bit binding-hash cookie) reaches the request handler unchallenged, admitting all 174 attempts to tool execution. Panel (b) is the same module rebuilt with \texttt  {require\_\allowbreak  peer\_\allowbreak  cred = 1}: all 500 attempts are rejected at the new peer-credential check before the request reaches the registry walks. The DENY-path median latency is unchanged between the two conditions, so the additional check imposes no measurable runtime cost.}}{40}{figure.12}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:chapter4-e4-peer-cred}{{12}{40}{Cross-UID hijack outcomes by attack sub-case (\texttt {blind}, \texttt {guessed}, \texttt {leaked}) and binary state, $n = 500$ per panel. Panel (a) is the stock module: only the \texttt {leaked} sub-case (where UID $B$ has obtained UID $A$'s 64-bit binding-hash cookie) reaches the request handler unchallenged, admitting all 174 attempts to tool execution. Panel (b) is the same module rebuilt with \texttt {require\_\allowbreak peer\_\allowbreak cred = 1}: all 500 attempts are rejected at the new peer-credential check before the request reaches the registry walks. The DENY-path median latency is unchanged between the two conditions, so the additional check imposes no measurable runtime cost}{figure.12}{}}
